lenders.name: Abdu
lenders.occupational_info:
My life is about business. Since I was a young boy in Eritrea, I did not want to depend on anyone. My father passed away when I was a baby so my mother raised me. When I saw her sacrifice for the family, I wanted to earn money to help. I started my first business in third grade, making hard caramel candy at home and selling it at school. 

Growing up in Eritrea, I loved soccer but there were some days when we could not play because the ball had a hole. As a young entrepreneur, I would take two damaged balls home, cut them, and sew them together to make one perfect ball. The next day, everyone wondered where I found a new ball. This is who I am—I always take what is given to me and make it into something better. 

There was a war in Eritrea and we saw a lot of tough days. We had to leave as refugees when I was 14 or 15. At that time no one knew their age. We were too scared, there was too much killing. We walked from Eritrea to Sudan for a month and a half, moving at night and sleeping during the day. From Sudan we went to Italy and then we came to 
California.

In the San Francisco Bay Area, I worked part-time assembling technology while studying for my AA degree in Computer Science. After I graduated, I decided to go into 
business because I like talking to people and being on my feet. I went on to own a range of businesses including an apparel stand, an Eritrean restaurant, and a gas station. Finally, 10 years ago I bought this food market store, Three Amigos.
